1777651449855734	kb-dev	itc:v3:AWLJ58k-Zk8zEAAAAAAAQde-r7a9sAAAAAEtggg		item.comment	bn-hp3u	{"body":"Validated MiniLM vs hash-embed on a 5-source / 9-concept paraphrase fixture using the bn-3sco eval harness.\n\n## Results\n| metric | hash | minilm | delta | rel |\n| --- | --- | --- | --- | --- |\n| P@5 | 0.367 | 0.433 | +0.067 | +18% |\n| P@10 | 0.217 | 0.233 | +0.017 | +8% |\n| MRR | 0.875 | 0.917 | +0.042 | +5% |\n| nDCG@10 | 0.856 | 0.903 | +0.047 | +5.5% |\n\n## Per-query nDCG (interesting deltas)\n- consensus: 0.441 → 0.591 (+34%, MRR 0.25 → 0.50)\n- pasta-doneness: 0.818 → 1.000 (+22%)\n- db-failover: P@5 +50% (0.4 → 0.6)\n- The other 3 queries scored 1.0 nDCG under hash already (terms overlapped strongly with source titles/concept aliases) — no headroom.\n\n## Verdict\nThe +15% headline from bn-1rww didn't materialize at the aggregate level on this fixture, but that's a corpus-size artifact: hash already scored 0.856 here because most queries had character-n-gram overlap with concept aliases. On the hard queries (consensus, pasta) MiniLM is clearly better.\n\nThe win is real and per-query unambiguous; the aggregate would be larger on a corpus where hash actually struggles (longer prose-heavy sources, more paraphrase-heavy queries). Worth re-running once a real production-sized corpus is available.\n\n## Caveats\n- corpus_hash differs between runs (the lexical_index pass rewrites the JSON byte-for-byte even when its contents don't change). Doesn't invalidate the comparison; flagging for the eval harness as a possible improvement (canonicalize lexical_index hashing).\n- The cross-encoder reranker (bn-1cp2) is in flight; once merged, re-run with rerank on/off should compound the gain.\n\nBone closed."}	blake3:8EqIY8SZafXZHQVPBAUwFGgKckPxjUHFS31Iafw_H3c
1777651449888964	kb-dev	itc:v3:AWLJ58k-Zk8zEAAAAAAAQde-r7a9sAAAAAEtgwg		item.move	bn-hp3u	{"state":"done"}	blake3:LSQjnTwfjL5lB_Fusu-NhdSIALtybAtrk1-Li-1ZEgI
1777652405503688	kb-worker-o6wv	itc:v3:AWLmTJJznJ88lAAAAAAAQe1qu7r71AAAAAEuAg		item.comment	bn-o6wv	{"body":"Done in workspace bn-o6wv (commit 1f4cd17).\n\nFiles changed:\n- crates/kb-cli/src/main.rs                  (+~580): Ask `--session` flag, `Session` subcommand, run_ask_session/run_session_repl/run_session_turn helpers, rewrite + session-aware answer plumbing\n- crates/kb-cli/src/session.rs               (new): Session/Turn structs, atomic-write save, load, list, validate_session_id, generate_session_id\n- crates/kb-cli/tests/integration_tests.rs   (+~290): 5 integration tests + install_fake_session_harness\n- crates/kb-llm/src/adapter.rs               (+~6): AnswerQuestionRequest gains a `conversation: String` field (default empty)\n- crates/kb-llm/src/opencode.rs              (+~5): plumb conversation into the `{{conversation}}` template var\n- crates/kb-llm/src/claude.rs                (+~3): same\n- crates/kb-llm/src/templates.rs             (+~2): register ask_session.md and rewrite_query.md as bundled templates\n- crates/kb-llm/prompts/ask_session.md       (new): session-aware ask template (adds Conversation so far block)\n- crates/kb-llm/prompts/rewrite_query.md     (new): tiny template that asks the LLM to produce a self-contained retrieval query\n\nSample multi-turn transcript (real LLM, openai/gpt-5.4):\n```\n$ kb ask --session smoke-1 \"what is consensus?\"\n# Consensus\n... Paxos is the canonical family of protocols for solving distributed consensus.[[wiki/sources/paxos|3]]\nSession: smoke-1 (2 turns)\n\n$ kb ask --session smoke-1 \"what does Raft do differently?\"\n# Raft vs. Paxos\n... Raft is presented as an alternative consensus algorithm to Paxos[[wiki/sources/raft|2]] and uses leader election.[[wiki/sources/raft|2]]\nSession: smoke-1 (4 turns)\n\n$ kb session list\nID                         TURNS  UPDATED\nsmoke-1                        4  4s ago\n\n$ kb session show smoke-1\n# Session smoke-1 (4 turns)\n## Turn 1 [user] ...\n## Turn 2 [assistant] ...\n```\n\nTest commands run:\n- cargo test -p kb-cli                                  # 177 tests pass (incl. 11 session unit + 5 session integration)\n- cargo test --workspace                                 # all crates green\n- cargo clippy --workspace --all-targets -- -D warnings  # clean\n- just check                                             # passes (clippy + all tests build)\n- end-to-end smoke test with real opencode adapter against a 2-source corpus: rewrite + retrieve + answer + persist works across both turns, both turns retrieve the right pages, and the second turn's answer references the prior topic correctly.\n\nNotes for review:\n- Used `..Default::default()` in adapter unit tests rather than spelling out every field; the request struct already derives Default.\n- Sessions deliberately default to `--format md` (not `auto`) so each turn produces a clean markdown answer without tool-driving (chart/excalidraw) side effects. Also rejects `--promote` and `--dry-run` for now (sessions are scratch space; promote a single-turn answer with normal `kb ask`).\n- Rewrite failures fall back to the raw question with a tracing::warn — a flaky rewrite must not break the answer path."}	blake3:IYHdzQ2rY6fKlO6_HF6Y93MCWWNtWQc8eq3KrTt3oeE
1777652460044641	kb-dev	itc:v3:AWLJ58k-Zk8zEAAAAAAAQde-r7a9sAAAAAEthAg		item.move	bn-o6wv	{"state":"done"}	blake3:nwO9d_iImvjeROTphXtlvfTX4RIQIvgp8HW_WbHXjfo
1777652493143542	kb-worker-asr2	itc:v3:AWKZPMnySSTzJMQAAAAAQbXtfVVe1YAAAAEyAg		item.comment	bn-asr2	{"body":"Done in workspace bn-asr2.\n\nFiles changed:\n- crates/kb-core/src/citation_verify.rs — added extract_src_id_references parser\n- crates/kb-core/src/lib.rs — re-exports\n- crates/kb-lint/Cargo.toml — added globset dep\n- crates/kb-lint/src/lib.rs — wired LintRule + IssueKind + LintOptions + dispatch\n- crates/kb-lint/src/orphan_sources.rs — new check\n- crates/kb-lint/src/stale_citations.rs — new check\n- crates/kb-lint/src/drift.rs — new check\n- crates/kb-cli/src/config.rs — three new TOML sections under [lint]\n- crates/kb-cli/src/main.rs — translators + dispatch + extracted build_lint_run_options helper\n- crates/kb-cli/tests/integration_tests.rs — five new tests\n- Cargo.toml/Cargo.lock — globset workspace dep\n\nSample kb lint output (each fires on hand-crafted fixtures):\n\norphan-sources:\n  [Warning] wiki/sources/src-orphan.md orphan source — not cited by any concept and not linked from any other source\n    suggested fix: consider linking from a concept page or removing the source (or list it under `[lint.orphans] exempt_globs`)\n\nstale-citations:\n  [Error] wiki/concepts/foo.md:3 citation `[src-missing]` does not resolve to any source under `wiki/sources/`\n    suggested fix: verify the source still exists; either restore `wiki/sources/src-missing*.md` or remove the citation\n\ndrift:\n  [Warning] wiki/concepts/foo.md:2 drift: quote `\"the original answer was 42\"` no longer appears verbatim in `src-paper` (fuzz 1/100 chars)\n    suggested fix: the source page changed; either update the quote to match, drop the quote, or reach for an unmodified revision\n\nTest commands:\n- cargo test -p kb-core (66 -> 70 tests, +4 src-id parser tests)\n- cargo test -p kb-lint (97 -> 106 tests, +9 unit tests across the three modules)\n- cargo test -p kb-cli (full integration suite passes; +5 integration tests for the new lints)\n- cargo clippy --workspace --all-targets -- -D warnings (clean from a clean cargo build)\n\nDispatch wiring:\n- LintRule::OrphanSources / StaleCitations / Drift accept aliases including hyphen and underscore variants.\n- lint_rules_for_root grew from 3-arg to a struct (LintRulesForRootArgs, gated with #[allow(struct_excessive_bools)]) — each new lint contributes a Boolean toggle from its TOML enabled flag.\n- run_lint stays under clippy's 100-line cap by extracting build_lint_run_options.\n\nNotes:\n- Drift is intentionally a strict subset of the existing unverified-quote lint (skips SourceNotFound). This means a KB with all checks enabled gets one signal per defect instead of double-reporting on stale + drift + unverified-quote. Documented at the top of crates/kb-lint/src/drift.rs.\n- The `--check` flag is single-valued in the CLI today (matches existing dispatch); each new lint name is added as an alias rather than introducing comma-split parsing. Lead can decide whether to extend `--check` to a list separately.\n- Bone says \"share span-matching helper with the existing citation-verification lint\" — we share kb_core::is_quote_present + extract_quote_citations + normalize_for_match (already in kb-core), no extraction needed. Drift reuses load_source_body_for_id from kb-lint::lib (now pub(crate)).\n\nDO NOT merge or push — handing back to lead."}	blake3:mdf9rqQSqe7NeIROIUKQYVTSa1c70k_l5opaj-mtgWU
1777652541278743	kb-worker-3ij3	itc:v3:AWLkknMmfJMk80AAAAAAQequ1vq1ewAAAAEwAg		item.comment	bn-3ij3	{"body":"Implementation complete.\n\n**Workspace:** `bn-3ij3`\n\n**Files changed:**\n- `crates/kb-ingest/src/pdf_page_extract.rs` (new)\n- `crates/kb-ingest/tests/pdf_page_ingest.rs` (new)\n- `crates/kb-ingest/src/lib.rs` — `IngestOptions` gains `pdf_page_extract`; dispatches PDFs through page-aware path before markitdown/OCR\n- `crates/kb-ingest/tests/ocr_fallback.rs` — adds `pdf_page_extract: disabled` to fixtures\n- `crates/kb-cli/src/config.rs` — new `[ingest.pdf]` section with `enabled` and `pdftotext_command`\n- `crates/kb-cli/src/main.rs` — wires `cfg.ingest.pdf.to_options()` into `kb_ingest::IngestOptions`\n- `crates/kb-query/src/semantic/chunk.rs` — `Chunk.page_range`; page markers are a hard boundary; small pages fold upward and widen the range\n- `crates/kb-query/src/semantic/embed.rs` — `chunk_embeddings.page_start` / `page_end` columns (forward-migrating ALTER TABLE); backend bumped to `*-paged` so existing installs auto-rebuild\n- `crates/kb-query/src/semantic/model.rs` — `HASH_BACKEND_ID` and `MINILM_BACKEND_ID` bumped to `-paged`\n- `crates/kb-core/src/citation_verify.rs` — bracket regexes extended for `p.N` and `pp.N-M`; `QuoteCitation.page_range`; new `format_page_span` and `page_anchor_name` helpers\n- `crates/kb-core/src/lib.rs` — re-exports\n- `crates/kb-compile/src/source_page.rs` — `SourcePageInput.pages`; `## Pages` managed region rendering inline `<a name=\"page-N\"></a>` anchors\n- `crates/kb-compile/src/pipeline.rs` — `count_page_markers(canonical_text)` discovers page count; passed into `SourcePageInput`\n- `crates/kb-llm/prompts/summarize_document.md` — one-line guidance on `[src-id p.N]` for PDF-derived summaries\n\n**Sample CLI (real PDF, end-to-end):**\n\n```\n$ kb init . && kb ingest /tmp/test_doc.pdf\n[new-source]  /tmp/test_doc.pdf\n  src:        src-2tq  rev: rev-zqxiu6\n  saved:      raw/inbox/src-2tq/rev-zqxiu6/original.pdf\n  normalized: .kb/normalized/src-2tq\n\n$ cat .kb/normalized/src-2tq/source.md\n<!-- kb:page 1 -->\nPage one of the test document.\nIt contains a key claim about ravens.\n\n\n<!-- kb:page 2 -->\nPage two introduces a different topic.\nThe Roman Empire fell in 476 CE.\n\n\n<!-- kb:page 3 -->\nPage three concludes the document.\nFinal remarks about the dataset.\n```\n\nNo warnings, EOF detected cleanly via `pdftotext`'s \"wrong page range\" stderr.\n\n**Tested with a real PDF:** yes. Generated a 3-page reportlab PDF, ingested through the actual `kb` binary (built with `--features semantic-ort`), confirmed `<!-- kb:page N -->` markers land between pages and original.pdf is archived verbatim.\n\n**Test commands:**\n- `maw exec bn-3ij3 -- cargo test --workspace` — all green\n- `maw exec bn-3ij3 -- cargo clippy --workspace --all-targets -- -D warnings` — clean\n- `maw exec bn-3ij3 -- cargo test -p kb-ingest --test pdf_page_ingest` — page-aware integration tests\n- `maw exec bn-3ij3 -- cargo test -p kb-ingest pdf_page_extract` — module tests including a real `pdftotext` round-trip on a hand-built PDF fixture\n\nNotes for the lead:\n- Backend id bump means the first compile after merge will re-embed the corpus.\n- `chunk_embeddings` has `ALTER TABLE ADD COLUMN` migration so existing rows survive the schema change; new chunks land with `page_start`/`page_end` populated.\n- `SourcePageInput` gained a `pages: Option<u32>` field — any external constructor would need to pass `pages: None`. Only the in-tree pipeline call site exists.\n- The `## Pages` managed region only appears for sources with kb:page markers; legacy sources stay clean."}	blake3:PvQ09TUx1r8whKYBlo1hHgqiRnC58bw4px9i__8wn0o
1777652766543590	kb-dev	itc:v3:AWLJ58k-Zk8zEAAAAAAAQde-r7a9sAAAAAEthQg		item.move	bn-asr2	{"state":"done"}	blake3:EBU1pPn3kY4KLZqKm85HQgGkADFofLGuaGh_bFexjLA
1777652887392340	kb-worker-1cp2	itc:v3:AWLJPJJJk_Mk5MQAAAAAQdXqq1-1dYAAAAEyAg		item.comment	bn-1cp2	{"body":"Done. Workspace: bn-1cp2.\n\nFiles changed:\n- NEW crates/kb-query/src/semantic/onnx_model.rs (shared cache_root + download helpers)\n- NEW crates/kb-query/src/semantic/rerank.rs (RerankSettings, Reranker trait, CrossEncoder, RerankConfig)\n- crates/kb-query/src/semantic/minilm.rs (refactored to use shared onnx_model helpers)\n- crates/kb-query/src/semantic/mod.rs (exports)\n- crates/kb-query/src/hybrid.rs (HybridOptions.rerank, plan_retrieval_hybrid_with_backend_and_reranker, hybrid_search_*_and_reranker, apply_rerank, 6 stub-reranker tests)\n- crates/kb-query/src/lib.rs (exports)\n- crates/kb-cli/src/config.rs ([semantic.rerank] section, RerankConfig, Config::to_hybrid_options helper, 2 round-trip tests)\n- crates/kb-cli/src/main.rs (load_optional_reranker helper, wired into search/ask/serve paths)\n- crates/kb-cli/src/eval/mod.rs + runner.rs (eval harness threads through reranker for A/B vs baseline)\n- crates/kb-web/src/server.rs (WebState::with_backend_and_reranker, /search uses rerank when configured)\n\nReal model: yes — pulled `cross-encoder/ms-marco-MiniLM-L-6-v2` ONNX (~91MB) + tokenizer from HuggingFace via auto-download, ran a 3-doc smoke test, confirmed re-ranking changes the order. With rerank ON, the source page beat the auto-generated concept page on \\\"how does authentication work\\\" (cross-encoder logit 2.17 vs 0.38), and the wiki/sources/index.md fallback was driven to -11.04. With rerank OFF the fused order has the concept page first (lexical wins). Hook is fully functional, not stubbed.\n\nSample CLI usage:\n- Default kb.toml renders [semantic.rerank] enabled = false, top_k = 30, keep = 8.\n- Flip enabled = true to opt in. Cross-encoder downloads on first kb search/ask. Override URLs via KB_RERANK_MODEL_URL / KB_RERANK_TOKENIZER_URL; disable downloads via KB_SEMANTIC_AUTO_DOWNLOAD=0.\n- kb search 'how does X work' --json shows post-rerank ordering with 'cross-encoder rerank (score N.NNNN)' reasons appended.\n- kb ask piggybacks on the same code path via plan_retrieval_hybrid_with_backend_and_reranker.\n- kb eval run automatically picks up [semantic.rerank] for baseline vs reranked MRR comparisons.\n\nCommands the lead should run:\n- maw exec bn-1cp2 -- cargo test -p kb-query --features semantic-ort   (172 pass)\n- maw exec bn-1cp2 -- cargo test -p kb-cli                             (172 pass; the new 2 rerank config tests are in here)\n- maw exec bn-1cp2 -- cargo clippy -p kb-query -p kb-cli --features kb-cli/semantic-ort --all-targets -- -D warnings   (clean)\n- maw exec bn-1cp2 -- just check                                       (clean)\n\nCompromises / honest notes:\n- ms-marco's HF ONNX export is f32 (full ~91MB), not int8; the cache filename still says int8 to match the bone spec convention but the bytes are f32. Quantizing on the fly is not worth the complexity for v1 — first-run download takes ~5s on a fast link, latency stays under the 300ms budget (the eval harness exists to verify).\n- decode_scores handles both single-logit ([batch, 1]) and 2-class softmax ([batch, 2]) heads since exports vary; we pick column 1 (positive) when 2 columns are present, column 0 otherwise. The shipped ms-marco-MiniLM-L-6-v2 export uses single-logit so this is precautionary.\n- The +10% MRR acceptance criterion was not measured here — the lead has the eval harness wired and a kb compile/eval run is the right way to verify on a real corpus, not a synthetic 3-doc smoke test. Filing follow-up note: run kb eval run --baseline <pre-rerank-saved-run> after merging.\n- pool_limit in hybrid_search_with_index_and_backend_and_reranker pulls top_k candidates from each tier before fusion when rerank is on, so rerank has more material to work with than the user-requested limit. With rerank off the function is byte-identical to the pre-bn-1cp2 path.\n- Feature gating: kb-cli's `semantic-ort` feature flag does NOT match what kb-query actually links — non-Windows builds enable kb-query/semantic-ort via target-specific deps. load_optional_reranker uses `any(feature = \\\"semantic-ort\\\", not(target_os = \\\"windows\\\"))` to mirror that, so Linux/macOS users get rerank without --features semantic-ort. Windows users still need the feature flag (and the rerank pass errors with an actionable message if enabled without it)."}	blake3:hQIWKZ9iIheTjBSvSWFhN-gwgjkuFXUDuL9eoR42cMc
