1777679049212523	kb-dev	itc:v3:AWLJ58k-Zk8zEAAAAAAAQde-r7a9sAAAAAEtlgg		item.create	bn-22m7	{"description":"Compile emits a 'Citations' block on every wiki/sources/<id>.md page that links to '../../.kb/normalized/<src-id>/source.md#<anchor>'. The target file exists on disk and the anchor is real, but 'kb lint' reports each one as an Error: 'unresolved wiki page target .kb/normalized/<src-id>/source'.\n\nRepro: kb init -> kb ingest <md> -> kb compile -> kb lint\nResult: every source gets one [Error] broken-links entry pointing at its own auto-generated citation. On the 7-source sourdough fixture (/tmp/kb-shake) this is 7 errors.\n\nThe lint is treating '.kb/normalized/<id>/source.md' as a wiki page target when it's a normalized-layer asset. Either:\n- broken-links should accept .kb/normalized/* paths as valid file links (file exists -> ok), or\n- the citation block should use a different link form that the lint recognizes.\n\nSeverity: makes 'kb lint' return non-zero on every freshly-compiled kb. False positive on 100% of sources.\n\nFound while smoke-testing bn-14tr.","kind":"task","title":"lint broken-links false-positive on auto-generated source citations"}	blake3:W6HRQoGnG10pNmqisxvtWtXjvPop4NBp5LZit9LrYmI
1777679058371254	kb-dev	itc:v3:AWLJ58k-Zk8zEAAAAAAAQde-r7a9sAAAAAEtlwg		item.create	bn-3jdo	{"description":"After 'kb compile' produces concept pages from sources, every concept's frontmatter lists its source(s) under 'source_document_ids:' and the source page has a '## Referenced by concepts' block listing back the concept names. But 'kb lint' (lint.orphans) reports every source as 'orphan source — not cited by any concept and not linked from any other source'.\n\nRepro: kb init -> kb ingest <md> -> kb compile -> kb lint -> see 7/7 sources flagged as orphans even though every concept page references them.\n\nThe orphan-source check appears to be looking for a different citation form than what the compile pipeline produces. It's likely scanning for [[wiki/sources/...]] backlinks but missing:\n- frontmatter source_document_ids: <id>\n- the kb:begin/end managed Referenced by concepts block in source pages\n- the kb:begin/end managed Backlinks block in concept pages\n\nSeverity: 100% false-positive rate. Makes lint.orphans unusable as-is. The Referenced by concepts block appears in every source page on /tmp/kb-shake including the ones the lint flags as orphans.\n\nFound while smoke-testing bn-14tr.","kind":"task","title":"lint orphan-sources false-positive: ignores concept source_document_ids backlinks"}	blake3:H_fO8TQKuaV4OrXY2Y1Vw73kHVoYaI1GqIvPI-_kCl4
1777679069430125	kb-dev	itc:v3:AWLJ58k-Zk8zEAAAAAAAQde-r7a9sAAAAAEtmAg		item.create	bn-3hgs	{"description":"On a 7-source sourdough kb (/tmp/kb-shake), compile timing breaks down as:\n- source_summary: 7 docs x ~6s = ~45s   (LLM per doc)\n- concept_extraction: 7 docs x ~17s = ~120s   (LLM per doc)\n- concept_merge: 248s for 31 candidates   (~8s/candidate)\n- everything else: <2s combined\n- total: 6:50\n\nThe merge stage looks like it's making one LLM call per pair or per candidate rather than batching. 31 candidates -> 248s suggests N or N^2 behavior in the LLM dispatch, not a single-batch dedup pass.\n\nSeverity: not a correctness bug, but it dominates total compile time on small/medium kbs and discourages iterative ingest+compile loops. Even a coarse batch (e.g. 'merge all candidates with shared category in one prompt') would likely cut this an order of magnitude.\n\nFound while smoke-testing bn-14tr.\n\nSuggested investigation:\n- Profile the prompt dispatch: are we firing 31 LLM calls or 1?\n- If 31: add a batched-merge prompt that takes the full candidate list\n- If 1: find out where the 248s is going (LLM latency? local pre/post?)","kind":"task","title":"compile concept_merge is slow: 248s for 31 candidates on tiny corpus"}	blake3:t08DrXVjBUMzIbv3u-cLP5Bvjeq9Ctfudi0zJsin7QA
1777679075316344	kb-dev	itc:v3:AWLJ58k-Zk8zEAAAAAAAQde-r7a9sAAAAAEtmQg		item.create	bn-24u5	{"description":"Running 'kb status' prints:\n\n  kb status\n\n  ingested sources: 7\n  wiki source pages: 7\n  ...\n\nThe literal command name 'kb status' appears as the first line. Looks like leftover debug-echo. Cosmetic, but every other top-level command (kb lint, kb doctor, kb search, kb ask) goes straight to its real output.\n\nFound while smoke-testing bn-14tr. Easy fix.","kind":"task","title":"kb status echos 'kb status' as first line of output"}	blake3:-pivh_z3NjXjN-lWb6VOVHLLucZX3SmKKiQNgKvpyv4
