1777933903715885	kb-dev	itc:v3:AWLJ58k-Zk8zEAAAAAAAQde-r7a9sAAAAAEtqQg		item.move	bn-17t0	{"state":"done"}	blake3:ec_TxqJJsKNx118a4-t9PMVAzsHj4YLlxdpFnq6ZxoE
1777937901924336	kb-dev	itc:v3:AWLJ58k-Zk8zEAAAAAAAQde-r7a9sAAAAAEtqgg		item.create	bn-1s8y	{"description":"kb already declares Backend::Pi and main.rs accepts a 'pi' runner name in kb.toml, but the runner is currently a stub: backend dispatch at crates/kb-cli/src/main.rs:4034 routes both Opencode and Pi through OpencodeAdapter. The actual pi CLI uses different flags than opencode and offers properties opencode lacks (better isolation, multi-provider, structured JSON output) -- those properties are why we want pi for the per-doc parallelism that just landed in bn-17t0 (where opencode races on its own SQLite WAL setup when started in parallel).\n\nWhat. Add a real PiAdapter in crates/kb-llm/src/pi.rs that mirrors chief's contract (~/src/chief/ws/default/src/runner/pi.rs):\n\n  pi --print --no-extensions --no-skills --no-prompt-templates \\\n     --system-prompt <inline text> \\\n     [--provider <p>] [--model <m>] \\\n     --tools <list>  (default: read,grep,find,ls) \\\n     [--thinking <level>] \\\n     --session-dir <dir>  (default: <root>/.kb/pi-sessions) \\\n     [--session <file> | --no-session] \\\n     @<user-prompt-path>      # MUST be the last argument\n\nOutput is JSON (sometimes wrapped in triple-backtick-json fences -- strip them). Errors come on stderr; non-zero exit + stderr should propagate as LlmAdapterError::Other.\n\nThen update crates/kb-cli/src/main.rs:4034 so Backend::Pi instantiates PiAdapter, not OpencodeAdapter:\n\n  match backend {\n      Backend::ClaudeCode => ...,\n      Backend::Opencode   => OpencodeAdapter::new(...),\n      Backend::Pi         => PiAdapter::new(...),\n  }\n\nImplement the LlmAdapter trait the same way claude.rs and opencode.rs do -- render the prompt template, invoke the CLI, parse the JSON, return (response, ProvenanceRecord). Most of the heavy lifting can copy opencode.rs's structure since both produce JSON.\n\nClaude-routing invariant. The router (crates/kb-llm/src/router.rs) already refuses to route claude-family models to anything except Backend::ClaudeCode (RouterError::ClaudeCodeRequired). PiAdapter must inherit this guarantee: it should never be reachable for a claude-* model. Add a defense-in-depth check in PiAdapter::new (or each method) that errors loudly if the configured model is claude-family -- a belt-and-suspenders safety against future router refactors that might let one slip through.\n\nAcceptance.\n1. crates/kb-llm/src/pi.rs ships a real PiAdapter with command-builder matching chief's flag set.\n2. main.rs:4034 dispatches Backend::Pi -> PiAdapter::new, not OpencodeAdapter::new.\n3. Unit tests cover: (a) basic command-build, (b) command-build with session, (c) JSON-fence stripping, (d) refuses claude-* models.\n4. just check clean.\n5. Smoke test: 'kb compile' on /tmp/kb-shake with [llm.runners.pi] configured runs end-to-end successfully (the bn-17t0 parallelism should not race the way opencode does).\n\nWhy now. The bn-17t0 perf work surfaced opencode's PRAGMA-WAL race under concurrent invocation -- fixed by a serial warmup, but the underlying fragility remains. pi was designed for non-interactive agent runs and should handle parallel invocation cleanly, removing the warmup workaround. Filing this as a follow-up so the win compounds.\n\nReference. ~/src/chief/ws/default/src/runner/pi.rs is the canonical invocation contract -- copy it verbatim where the LlmAdapter trait shape allows, deviate only where chief's runner abstractions don't match kb-llm's.","kind":"task","title":"kb-llm: real pi adapter (mirror chief's invocation contract; non-claude models only)"}	blake3:jbxFTFrw-qIK76ltnz6vVpYPcW3Ah3DQIHBZ3L-Qm4c
1777937931094115	kb-dev	itc:v3:AWLJ58k-Zk8zEAAAAAAAQde-r7a9sAAAAAEtqwg		item.create	bn-1xlz	{"description":"After bn-1s8y lands a real pi adapter, the second step is to make pi the default runner kb auto-configures when it's available on PATH. Today 'kb init' writes a kb.toml that always defaults to opencode (default_runner = \"opencode\"). We want kb to detect 'pi' on PATH and prefer it over opencode for non-claude models, mirroring how chief's init detects runners (~/src/chief/ws/default/src/init.rs).\n\nWhat.\n1. In crates/kb-cli/src/init.rs (or wherever 'kb init' writes the bootstrap kb.toml), detect runners in this order:\n   - claude (always, for claude-family models per ToS)\n   - pi (preferred default for non-claude models, if 'pi' is on PATH)\n   - opencode (fallback when pi is not available)\n2. Set default_runner = \"pi\" when pi is detected; fall back to \"opencode\" otherwise.\n3. Pin default_model to a non-claude model that pi handles well (probably keep openai/gpt-5.4 to match the current default, unless pi's flag shape requires splitting provider+model -- in which case write the provider/model fields the pi runner section expects).\n4. The generated kb.toml's [llm.runners.pi] section should set tier/tools/thinking sensibly. Reference: chief writes:\n     [llm.runners.pi]\n     command = \"pi\"\n     tier = \"strong\"\n     type = \"agent\"\n     tools = \"read,grep,find,ls\"\n   kb's runner config doesn't have a 'tier' or 'type' field today, but the template should at least set: command, model, provider (if pi needs --provider), and tool flags consistent with kb's RunnerDef shape. Look at how kb's existing opencode/claude runner templates write their kb.toml sections and produce a similarly-shaped pi section.\n\n5. Add unit tests that cover:\n   (a) When pi is on PATH, init writes default_runner = \"pi\" and an [llm.runners.pi] section.\n   (b) When only opencode is on PATH, init writes default_runner = \"opencode\" (current behavior preserved).\n   (c) When neither is available, init writes default_runner = \"claude\" (or whatever the existing fallback is).\n\n6. Update kb's README / quick-start docs (if any reference the default runner) to say pi is preferred when available.\n\nAcceptance.\n- 'kb init' on a system with pi on PATH produces a kb.toml whose default_runner = \"pi\" and contains a usable [llm.runners.pi] section.\n- 'kb init' on a system without pi falls back to opencode unchanged.\n- 'kb compile' on /tmp/kb-shake with the auto-generated pi-default kb.toml runs end-to-end and produces equivalent output to the opencode default (same source pages, same concept extraction quality on a fresh corpus).\n- just check clean.\n- After this lands, the bn-17t0 serial-warmup workaround in pipeline.rs (run_one_doc_llm_job called once before the parallel pool) can be removed if pi handles parallel invocation cleanly. Track that as a separate cleanup follow-up; do not bundle into this bone.\n\nDepends on bn-1s8y (the real PiAdapter must exist first). Mark blocked-by accordingly.\n\nWhy now. opencode races on its own SQLite WAL setup when invoked in parallel (observed in bn-17t0 testing -- 3 of 7 first-time invocations failed). pi was designed for non-interactive agent calls, has cleaner isolation, and is the better default for kb's compile pipeline. Switching the default unlocks future parallelism work without per-runner workarounds.","kind":"task","title":"kb init: prefer pi over opencode as default runner when available"}	blake3:ZJkJzwj0ePRbG5QhAINojjVEzTo63Vb_udqZmr8nauc
