1777946113724011	kb-dev	itc:v3:AWLJ58k-Zk8zEAAAAAAAQde-r7a9sAAAAAEtsgg		item.move	bn-1xlz	{"state":"done"}	blake3:p5wupbW8rxPcpbq3j3YJWzNPZZ0OTlmrrVlQ0iJZLPQ
1778013469827871	kb-dev	itc:v3:AWLJ58k-Zk8zEAAAAAAAQde-r7a9sAAAAAEtswg		item.create	bn-mml0	{"description":"Two small follow-ups now that pi is the default runner (bn-1xlz merged) and PiAdapter is shipped (bn-1s8y).\n\n1) Remove the bn-17t0 warmup workaround when the runner is pi.\n\nThe warmup at crates/kb-compile/src/pipeline.rs in `prefetch_per_doc_llm` runs the first job serially before fanning out the rest, to dodge opencode's `PRAGMA journal_mode = WAL` race when N first-time invocations start at the same instant. Pi was designed for non-interactive concurrent use and does not exhibit this race — the warmup step costs ~5-8s for nothing on every pi-default compile (visible in the pi-default smoke test in /tmp/kb-shake: ~3:25 wallclock vs ~2:55 for opencode despite pi having stable parallelism).\n\nThe cleanest split is to detect the runner kind once at the call site and skip the warmup when it's pi. Easiest approach: thread a `RunnerKind` (or boolean `runner_serializes_init`) into `prefetch_per_doc_llm` so the function knows whether to do the serial first call. Default behavior on unknown runners stays \"do the warmup\" — strictly safer.\n\nAcceptance.\n- pipeline.rs no longer pays a serial warmup tax when `default_runner = \"pi\"` is configured.\n- Compile wallclock on /tmp/kb-shake with pi default drops by ~5-10s (one job's worth of latency).\n- opencode-default compiles continue to do the warmup unchanged (regression-test by configuring kb.toml to opencode and re-running).\n\n2) Add a kb doctor health check for runner/model slug compatibility.\n\nAfter bn-1xlz, `kb init` writes a default_model that matches the chosen default_runner (\"openai-codex/gpt-5.5\" for pi, \"openai/gpt-5.4\" for opencode, \"claude-sonnet-4-6\" for claude). Users editing kb.toml by hand can produce mismatches like default_runner=\"pi\" with default_model=\"openai/gpt-5.4\" — pi rejects that slug pattern with a \"No models match pattern\" warning and the call fails fast with confusing output.\n\nAdd a doctor check that:\n- Identifies the chosen default_runner.\n- Checks whether default_model is a known-friendly slug for that runner. Heuristic per runner:\n  - pi: provider/id slugs where provider matches one of pi's recognized providers (openai-codex, anthropic, google, groq, ...). The user's authenticated providers in ~/.pi/agent/auth.json are the strongest signal — if the file is readable, prefer that list; otherwise fall back to a hard-coded short list.\n  - opencode: provider/id slugs where provider matches what opencode supports.\n  - claude: bare claude-* or claude/* or anthropic/* slugs.\n- Emits a warning when the slug shape is wrong, with an actionable hint (e.g., \"default_model='openai/gpt-5.4' is opencode-shaped but default_runner='pi' — pi expects 'openai-codex/...' or another provider it supports. Run `kb init --reset-config --force` to regenerate, or edit kb.toml.\").\n- Does not error — kb doctor surfaces it as a yellow warning so the user can investigate and fix.\n\nAcceptance.\n- New check appears in `kb doctor` output (named e.g. \"model_slug_matches_runner\").\n- Triggers a warning on the misconfiguration: default_runner=\"pi\", default_model=\"openai/gpt-5.4\".\n- Stays silent on the well-formed configs kb init produces today.\n- Unit tests cover: pi+pi-shaped (ok), pi+opencode-shaped (warn), opencode+opencode-shaped (ok), claude+claude-shaped (ok), claude+non-claude-shaped (warn).\n\nFiled because both are small, both are direct follow-ups to bn-1s8y/bn-1xlz, and the warmup tax is observable on every pi compile until #1 lands.","kind":"task","title":"post-pi cleanup: drop bn-17t0 warmup for pi + kb doctor runner/model slug check"}	blake3:u7sX-gur-b1C-4umysBgGHn7NDzZ47rGGhwP2s6IA_U
1778016892933092	kb-dev	itc:v3:AWLJ58k-Zk8zEAAAAAAAQde-r7a9sAAAAAEttgg		item.create	bn-1j4l	{"description":"Dogfood review finding from a fake KB at /tmp/kb-review.WbXylN.\n\nRepro:\n1. Run `kb serve --root /tmp/kb-review.WbXylN --port 18543`.\n2. POST to `/ask` with a normal question.\n3. Response returns success with `\"answer\":\"\"`, `\"artifact_path\":\"outputs/questions/.../answer.md\"`, and `\"error\":null` even though the CLI artifact exists under the KB root.\n\nLikely cause:\n- crates/kb-web/src/server.rs reads the CLI JSON `artifact_path` directly via `std::fs::read_to_string(p).ok()` instead of joining relative paths to the configured KB root.\n- The read failure is swallowed, so the web API reports a successful empty answer.\n\nExpected:\n- Root-relative artifact paths should be resolved against the served KB root.\n- If the artifact cannot be read, `/ask` should return an explicit error instead of an empty successful answer.\n\nUseful pointers:\n- crates/kb-web/src/server.rs around the `/ask` handler's `artifact_path` parsing and `read_to_string` call.","kind":"bug","labels":["dogfood","review"],"size":"s","title":"web /ask returns success with empty answer when artifact_path is root-relative"}	blake3:nfNwOxxXGhy4zcb9XZ6xAzv1j0D4rOJMJh94spvYZo0
1778016892969031	kb-dev	itc:v3:AWLJ58k-Zk8zEAAAAAAAQde-r7a9sAAAAAEttwg		item.create	bn-36hw	{"description":"Dogfood review finding from a fake KB at /tmp/kb-review.WbXylN.\n\nRepro:\n1. Ingest and compile a KB with source docs that extract concepts.\n2. Confirm `.kb/state/graph.json` exists and includes concept/source/wiki nodes.\n3. Run `kb inspect --trace concept:operational-telemetry --json`.\n4. Run `kb inspect --trace src-156 --json`.\n\nObserved:\n- `graph: null` and empty trace output, even though graph.json exists.\n- Concept nodes in graph.json have empty inputs/outputs.\n\nLikely cause:\n- The merge stage records absolute wiki paths and candidate names in build records.\n- The graph node normalization path does not map those IDs back to wiki-page/concept nodes, so source/concept edges are not created.\n\nExpected:\n- `inspect --trace` should show useful provenance from sources to wiki pages to concepts.\n- Concept nodes should have source/page inputs where applicable.\n\nUseful pointers:\n- crates/kb-compile/src/pipeline.rs graph build record normalization.\n- `graph_node_for_id` does not appear to handle absolute `wiki/concepts/...` paths.","kind":"bug","labels":["dogfood","review"],"size":"s","title":"inspect --trace returns null graph for concepts and sources after compile"}	blake3:8jVG0AJfWblM109jcEp1WGb-uoJaKL1WrKBchF6o-5w
1778016893009988	kb-dev	itc:v3:AWLJ58k-Zk8zEAAAAAAAQde-r7a9sAAAAAEtuAg		item.create	bn-1ure	{"description":"Dogfood/code review finding.\n\nObserved:\n- `CaptionsConfig` exposes `runner` and `model`, and default docs imply captions can choose a caption-specific runner/model.\n- `to_pipeline_config` only passes enabled/allow_paths/prompt into the compile pipeline.\n- `run_compile_action` builds one default adapter and passes that same adapter to all compile stages, including captions.\n\nImpact:\n- A user can configure `compile.captions.runner = \"claude\"` and `model = \"claude-haiku-4-5\"`, but those values do not actually control caption generation.\n- If the default runner is non-vision or not appropriate for captions, the caption-specific config is misleading.\n\nExpected:\n- Caption runner/model config should either be honored by creating a caption-specific adapter, or removed/renamed so the configuration surface is honest.\n\nUseful pointers:\n- crates/kb-cli/src/config.rs `CaptionsConfig` and `to_pipeline_config`.\n- crates/kb-cli/src/main.rs compile adapter construction.","kind":"bug","labels":["dogfood","review"],"size":"s","title":"compile.captions runner and model config are ignored"}	blake3:KFMFHqHXEaPdiLxtRaSp2UovwwGn26p7rL0IG_yP9u0
1778016893044675	kb-dev	itc:v3:AWLJ58k-Zk8zEAAAAAAAQde-r7a9sAAAAAEtuQg		item.create	bn-2dzn	{"description":"Dogfood review finding from a fake KB at /tmp/kb-review.WbXylN.\n\nRepro:\n1. Configure a publish target.\n2. Run `kb publish --json <target>`.\n\nObserved:\n- Output is a raw `PublishReport` object beginning with fields like `target`, `destination`, and `dry_run`.\n- It does not include the common CLI JSON envelope fields used by most other commands, such as `schema_version`, `command`, `data`, `warnings`, and `errors`.\n\nImpact:\n- Automation cannot treat publish JSON like the rest of the CLI.\n- This regresses the stable JSON contract expected by agent/tool integrations.\n\nExpected:\n- `publish --json` should use the same envelope helper as other commands, with the publish report under `data`.\n\nUseful pointer:\n- crates/kb-cli/src/publish.rs currently prints `serde_json::to_string_pretty(&report)` directly.","kind":"bug","labels":["dogfood","review"],"size":"s","title":"publish --json bypasses the common CLI JSON envelope"}	blake3:x3IyfFuL-Av-XXBse6agCLHwC0bCTeLzOX8kC64gW90
1778016893081620	kb-dev	itc:v3:AWLJ58k-Zk8zEAAAAAAAQde-r7a9sAAAAAEtugg		item.create	bn-17ba	{"description":"Dogfood review finding from a fake KB at /tmp/kb-review.WbXylN.\n\nRepro:\n1. Compile a KB with hash semantic search and lexical index.\n2. Run `kb search --json telemetry`.\n\nObserved:\n- Some result fields serialize absent ranks as `18446744073709551615`, for example `lexical_rank` or `semantic_rank`.\n\nImpact:\n- The JSON API leaks an implementation sentinel into user-facing output.\n- Human readers and downstream tools get nonsense rank values instead of a clear absence marker.\n\nExpected:\n- Missing ranks should serialize as `null` or be omitted from JSON output.\n- Internal sentinel values should stay internal.\n\nUseful pointers:\n- crates/kb-query/src/hybrid.rs documents/uses `usize::MAX` as the missing-rank sentinel.","kind":"bug","labels":["dogfood","review"],"size":"s","title":"hybrid search JSON exposes usize::MAX sentinel ranks"}	blake3:LkuzOd68nvyLsw_eGJIp_UiZUcP0t-VrQXsXn7aXHR4
1778016893119649	kb-dev	itc:v3:AWLJ58k-Zk8zEAAAAAAAQde-r7a9sAAAAAEtuwg		item.create	bn-6mqt	{"description":"Dogfood rough edge from a fake KB at /tmp/kb-review.WbXylN.\n\nRepro:\n1. Run `kb compile --json` on a KB with multiple changed sources.\n2. Compare with the non-JSON compile output and stderr progress.\n\nObserved:\n- The JSON response is mostly totals/summary.\n- Detailed per-stage/pass information is not represented in structured JSON, while human-oriented progress still appears separately.\n\nImpact:\n- Agents and automation have a harder time explaining what compile actually did.\n- Users asking for machine-readable output lose useful diagnostics compared with the pretty path.\n\nExpected:\n- `compile --json` should include structured per-stage details such as sources processed, pages generated, concepts merged, indexes refreshed, assets handled, and cache hits/misses.","kind":"bug","labels":["dogfood","review"],"size":"s","title":"compile --json omits per-stage compile details that are visible in human output"}	blake3:RWKWsUMJLFEuZDPg3_IQD4GDBaAehH8iTqWzcGD9K-8
1778016893272624	kb-dev	itc:v3:AWLJ58k-Zk8zEAAAAAAAQde-r7a9sAAAAAEtvAg		item.create	bn-pze3	{"description":"Dogfood rough edge from a fake KB at /tmp/kb-review.WbXylN.\n\nRepro:\n1. Run `kb init`.\n2. Ingest several sources.\n3. Run `kb status --json` before the first successful compile.\n\nObserved:\n- The response reported `total_sources: 3` but nested source totals still showed zero before compile.\n- After compile, the counts normalized.\n\nImpact:\n- Freshly ingested KBs look internally inconsistent to users and agents.\n- Automation has to guess which count is authoritative.\n\nExpected:\n- Status should present one coherent source count model before and after compile, or clearly label pre-compile pending input counts separately from compiled source counts.","kind":"bug","labels":["dogfood","review"],"size":"s","title":"status JSON reports inconsistent source totals before first compile"}	blake3:AP8g6X-YbblLA_6Uw2pCRAeSZ2shNCWfPr2LA0gci7A
1778016893324269	kb-dev	itc:v3:AWLJ58k-Zk8zEAAAAAAAQde-r7a9sAAAAAEtvQg		item.create	bn-1ptp	{"description":"Dogfood rough edge from a fake KB at /tmp/kb-review.WbXylN.\n\nRepro:\n1. Run `kb forget --dry-run --json <source-id>`.\n2. Inspect the cascade refresh fields.\n\nObserved:\n- Dry-run output used mutation-sounding/past-tense fields such as `index_pages_refreshed`, `lexical_index_refreshed`, and `graph_nodes_pruned`.\n- These values describe the preview of what would happen, not work that actually happened.\n\nImpact:\n- Machine-readable dry-run output is easy to misread as already-applied mutation state.\n- This is especially risky for destructive commands like forget.\n\nExpected:\n- Dry-run JSON should use preview-oriented names, or include explicit per-field metadata that the values are planned effects only.","kind":"bug","labels":["dogfood","review"],"size":"s","title":"forget --dry-run JSON uses past-tense mutation fields for previewed cascade work"}	blake3:O9EsS9P7ApKJFQgxExuvHuKlawa_pXlnyWBBhwrpyDg
