1778037933569785	kb-dev	itc:v3:AWLJ58k-Zk8zEAAAAAAAQde-r7a9sAAAAAEt4wg		item.create	bn-1588	{"description":"Third dogfood review finding from installed `kb` (`/home/bob/.cargo/bin/kb`, version 0.1.0) against fresh fake KB `/tmp/kb-pass3.6Pq213`.\n\nRepro:\n1. Configure `[llm.runners.opencode]` in `kb.toml`.\n2. Run:\n   `kb chat --root /tmp/kb-pass3.6Pq213 --dry-run --json`\n\nObserved:\n- Exit code is 0.\n- Stdout is plain runner text, not a JSON envelope:\n  `A launch runway diagram with staged rollout checkpoints and telemetry guardrails.`\n- The command still invokes the configured opencode command instead of behaving like a dry-run.\n\nExpected:\n- With `--json`, output should use the standard CLI JSON envelope.\n- With `--dry-run`, the command should not spawn the interactive runner; it should report the generated config/prompt path or planned command.\n- If `kb chat` intentionally does not support global `--json`/`--dry-run`, it should reject those flags explicitly rather than silently ignoring them.\n\nLikely cause / pointers:\n- The top-level chat branch accepts global flags but calls `chat::run_chat(chat_root, model_override)` without passing `cli.dry_run` or `cli.json`.\n- `chat::run_chat` always writes the prompt/config and calls the interactive spawn path.\n- Source pointers: `crates/kb-cli/src/main.rs` around the `Command::Chat` branch, and `crates/kb-cli/src/chat.rs::run_chat`.","kind":"bug","labels":["dogfood","pass3","review"],"size":"s","title":"chat --dry-run --json ignores flags and prints plain runner output"}	blake3:XMk8vxoa5DNFsO4r9_57V0KkIWwhPOZ2ale6i4TgdaA
1778037933603640	kb-dev	itc:v3:AWLJ58k-Zk8zEAAAAAAAQde-r7a9sAAAAAEt5Ag		item.create	bn-3qy6	{"description":"Third dogfood review rough edge from installed `kb` (`/home/bob/.cargo/bin/kb`, version 0.1.0) against fresh fake KB `/tmp/kb-pass3.6Pq213`.\n\nPrior related bones were fixed:\n- `bn-36hw`: original empty trace / graph JSON issue.\n- `bn-238c`: graph.db edges existed but trace was empty.\n\nCurrent repro:\n1. Compile a KB with linked source and concept pages.\n2. Confirm `.kb/state/graph.db` contains edges, for example:\n   - `wiki/concepts/operational-telemetry.md -> wiki/sources/src-2s8-runway-release-playbook.md`\n   - `wiki/sources/src-2s8-runway-release-playbook.md -> wiki/concepts/operational-telemetry.md`\n3. Run:\n   `kb inspect --root /tmp/kb-pass3.6Pq213 --json --trace concept:operational-telemetry`\n\nObserved:\n- `trace` is now non-empty, so this is improved.\n- `graph` is still `null`, which is surprising for `--trace` JSON.\n- The recursive trace walks wiki link/backlink relationships and cycles through related concepts/sources rather than presenting a clean provenance tree. For example, `operational-telemetry` traces into source pages, then into other concept pages, then back into sources.\n\nExpected:\n- Either populate `graph` with the directly relevant graph nodes/edges, or remove/rename the field if the supported output is `trace` only.\n- The trace should distinguish provenance/dependency edges from ordinary wiki backlinks, or expose edge types so consumers can tell what relationship they are looking at.\n- Recursive output should be cycle-aware in a way that avoids repeated/circular-looking nested structures.\n\nImpact:\n- The command is now usable, but agent/API consumers still have to reverse-engineer what `trace` means, and `graph: null` makes the JSON contract look partially broken.","kind":"bug","labels":["dogfood","pass3","review"],"size":"s","title":"inspect --trace JSON still has graph null and a confusing recursive backlink trace"}	blake3:u8rGlVMhauoNKo312oMl9jMwA51IA8B8fPNAMX1sVCU
